TY  - JOUR
T1  - Does Past Success Lead Analysts to Become Overconfident?
AU  - Hilary, Gilles
AU  - Menzly, Lior
Y1  - 2006/04/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0485
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0485
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 489
EP  - 500
VL  - 52
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper provides evidence that analysts who have predicted earnings more accurately than the median analyst in the previous four quarters tend to be simultaneously less accurate and further from the consensus forecast in their subsequent earnings prediction. This phenomenon is economically and statistically meaningful. The results are robust to different estimation techniques and different control variables. Our findings are consistent with an attribution bias that leads analysts who have experienced a short-lived success to become overconfident in their ability to forecast future earnings.
AB  - This paper provides evidence that analysts who have predicted earnings more accurately than the median analyst in the previous four quarters tend to be simultaneously less accurate and further from the consensus forecast in their subsequent earnings prediction. This phenomenon is economically and statistically meaningful. The results are robust to different estimation techniques and different control variables. Our findings are consistent with an attribution bias that leads analysts who have experienced a short-lived success to become overconfident in their ability to forecast future earnings.
