TY  - JOUR
T1  - Allocation of Service Time in a Multiserver System
AU  - El-Taha, Muhammad
AU  - Maddah, Bacel
Y1  - 2006/04/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0467
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0467
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 623
EP  - 637
VL  - 52
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Reducing congestion is a primary concern in the design and analysis of queueing networks, especially in systems where sources of randomness are characterized by high variability. This paper considers a multiserver first-come, first-served (FCFS) queueing model where we arrange servers in two stations in series. All arrivals join the first service center, where they receive a maximum of T units of service. Arrivals with service requirements that exceed the threshold T join the second queue, where they receive their remaining service. For a variety of heavy tail service time distributions, characterized by large coefficient of variations, analytical and numerical comparisons show that our scheme provides better system performance than the standard parallel multiserver model in the sense of reducing the mean delay per customer in heavy traffic systems. Our model is likely to be useful in systems where high variability is a cause for degradation and where numerous service interruptions are not desired.
AB  - Reducing congestion is a primary concern in the design and analysis of queueing networks, especially in systems where sources of randomness are characterized by high variability. This paper considers a multiserver first-come, first-served (FCFS) queueing model where we arrange servers in two stations in series. All arrivals join the first service center, where they receive a maximum of T units of service. Arrivals with service requirements that exceed the threshold T join the second queue, where they receive their remaining service. For a variety of heavy tail service time distributions, characterized by large coefficient of variations, analytical and numerical comparisons show that our scheme provides better system performance than the standard parallel multiserver model in the sense of reducing the mean delay per customer in heavy traffic systems. Our model is likely to be useful in systems where high variability is a cause for degradation and where numerous service interruptions are not desired.
